{{Infobox Theatre |name = Queen's Theatre, Dublin |image = Adelphi Theatre Dublin.jpg |caption = Adelphi Theatre (1829–1844) |address = [[Pearse Street, Dublin|Pearse Street]] |city = [[Dublin|Dublin 2]] |country = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] |designation = |latitude = |longitude = |architect = |owner = |capacity = |type = [[patent theatre]] |opened = 1829 |yearsactive = |rebuilt = 1909 |closed = 1969 |othernames = Adelphi Theatre |production = |currentuse = |website = }}
The '''Queen's Theatre, Dublin''', located in [[Pearse Street, Dublin|Pearse Street]] was originally built in 1829 as the '''Adelphi Theatre'''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Finegan|first1=John|title=Dublin's Lost Theatres|journal=Dublin Historical Record|date=1994|volume=47|issue=1|page=96}}</ref> This building was demolished in 1844 and rebuilt. It reopened that same year as the '''Queens Royal Theatre''',<ref name=Kerins>{{cite web|last1=Kerins|first1=Des|title=The Queen's Theatre|url=http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Dublin/QueensTheatreDublin.htm|website=arthurlloyd.co.uk|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> the new owner having been granted a Royal [[Letters Patent|Patent]] to operate as a [[patent theatre]]. The theatre quickly became known as simply the Queen's. It was most famous in the 20th century as the home of the Happy Gang, a troupe of comics, singers and musicians including [[Danny Cummins]], Jimmy Harvey, Mick Eustace and [[Cecil Nash]]. The regular members of the "gang" took part in sketches as required, but in addition each had to be a solo performer in his own right. The [[Abbey Theatre]] took over the building after the Abbey fire of 1951 and remained until 1966. The theatre closed in 1969 and was demolished in 1975.
==References== {{reflist}} *Ryan,<ref> </ref> Philip B. ''The Lost Theatres of Dublin''. (The Badger Press, 1998) {{ISBN|0-9526076-1-1}}
